Hi, @iftaken, do you happen to be hosting multiple onnx models on one machine as well? What kind of models have you been loading?

(I have a similar issue #7067, but I'm using the C# API and it may be semi-related to what I'm seeing)

The sample has a bug. The caller is responsible for freeing the memory that was allocated for InputName. Use the same allocator that was used for retrieving the name. Issue Free on it.

The C++ API is poorly documented, however, the C API that is being utilized by C++ has this [documented](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/include/onnxruntime/core/session/onnxruntime_c_api.h#L494)

I will check `InitializeWithDenormalAsZero`, however, it appears that it has to do with what OpenMP does.

```cpp

```

Hi, @yuslepukhin,  memory leak alse happend in python demo. 

```python
import os, psutil
import onnxruntime
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import tqdm

# https://github.com/onnx/models/tree/master/vision/classification/squeezenet
path = r"squeezenet1.1-7.onnx"
session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(path)
data = np.random.random((1, 3, 224, 224))
data = data.astype(np.float32)

input_data = [data]
inputs = {}
for i in range(len(input_data)):
    input_name = session.get_inputs()[i].name
    inputs[input_name] = input_data[i]

output_names = []
for i in range(len(session.get_outputs())):
    output_names.append(session.get_outputs()[i].name)


def test():
    process = psutil.Process(os.getpid())
    records = []
    for i in tqdm.tqdm(range(0, 10000)):
        res = session.run(output_names, inputs)
        records.append((i, process.memory_info().rss / 1024 / 1024))
    return records

records = test()
print(f"run 10000 time memory leak: {records[-1][1] - records[0][1]} Mb")
```
